{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510076","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510076"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:23:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:23:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11489"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11489","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11489"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.76,0.1,0.07,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4120"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107163"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4120","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4120"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11489"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89615"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1179"},{"type":"tags","id":"1617"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"},{"type":"tags","id":"4763"},{"type":"tags","id":"4772"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9664"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5085"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5128"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9008"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9409"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26989"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42610"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43234"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44361"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107163"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old woman presents to her General Practitioner with three days of new painful \u201clumps\u201d in her groin and feeling generally unwell. She has had two previous partners, and a history of a gonorrhoea infection two years ago. At the time, she was promptly treated with ceftriaxone and azithromycin and had resolution of the infection. She has been sexually active with her current partner for three months. They do not use barrier conception as she uses the oral contraceptive pill. They engage in oral and vaginal sex regularly. She is otherwise well and has  not travelled overseas for a number of years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination she has a temperature of 38.1 C. All other vital signs are normal. On inspection of the mouth and oral mucous membranes, there are no abnormalities. Abdominal examination does not reveal any localised or generalised tenderness or other abnormalities. On inspection of her genitalia there are several ulcers as well as tender, pruritic vesicles on her vulva.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Human Papilloma Virus (HPV)","Herpes Simplex Virus (HSV)","Syphilis","Chancroid","Candida albicans"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHerpes simplex virus (HSV)\u003C/strong\u003E best fits with the description in the question. There are two types: HSV-1 and HSV-2. HSV-1 tends to cause perioral lesions (cold sores) while HSV-2 tends to cause anogenital lesions, however, both types can cause lesions in both places. In a primary presentation of HSV, patients can often experience systemic symptoms such as fever, malaise, and lymphadenopathy. The mucocutaneous manifestations include a vesicular rash which may progress to pustules and ulcerations, as experienced by the patient in the question. The manifestations may tingle, itch, and are often painful. However, infections can often by asymptomatic as the virus lays dormant and hidden from the immune system which leads to recurrent presentations for many patients. Treatment is usually with oral antivirals such as valaciclovir for episodes of ulceration, however, some patients may remain on antivirals for suppression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESyphilis\u003C/strong\u003E is another STI which can cause ulceration as well as widespread lymphadenopathy. However, the ulcerations caused by syphilis, termed chancre, are usually painless. Syphilis also does not cause a vesicular rash. There are multiple stages of syphilis if it is left untreated. Primary syphilis involves chancre which are usually present at the initial site of infection (e.g. genitalia). Secondary syphilis is usually hallmarked by rash, malaise, and fever and occurs more than six weeks after initial infection. Tertiary syphilis occurs after a period of latency and can involve multiple organs including the heart and the brain (neurosyphilis). However, syphilis is known as the great masquerade due to its varied presentation which can mimic many other conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHuman papilloma virus (HPV)\u003C/strong\u003E is a virus that causes mucocutaneous infection. There are many types which are primarily transmitted through direct skin-to-skin contact. Most patients around the age of the patient in the question should have received vaccination for HPV if they grew up in Australia. It is important to note that the HPV vaccination is not 100% effective in preventing some of the HPV infections (and as such, being vaccinated would decrease the likelihood but not eliminate the possibility of HPV). The vaccination is to prevent cervical cancer and other cancers associated with HPV and protects against many sexually transmitted types. If the patient was not vaccinated or contracted a type of HPV not protected by vaccination, then the presentation would be that of genital warts rather than ulceration and vesicular rash.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChancroid\u003C/strong\u003E, caused by \u003Cem\u003EHaemophilus ducreyi\u003C/em\u003E, presents with painful genital ulcers and tender inguinal lymphadenopathy. However, it does not typically present with vesicles, and is extremely rare in Australia. The ulcers of chancroid are typically deeper and more irregular than those of HSV.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECandida albicans\u003C/strong\u003E causes vulvovaginal candidiasis which typically presents with white vaginal discharge, vulval itching, and erythema. While it can cause superficial erosions, it does not cause vesicles or ulcers, and systemic symptoms such as fever would be unusual.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["HSV infection can present with systemic symptoms (fever, lethargy) as well as genital signs and symptoms","The genital manifestation of HSV infections is characterised by multiple painful, pruritic vesicles around the genitals and rectum","Other important differentials for anogenital ulceration include syphilis, donovanosis and non-sexually transmitted pathology such as Beh\u00e7et disease, herpes zoster and many more."],"references":["Genital Herpes Simplex Virus (HSV). Australian STI Management Guidelines. https://sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/genital-herpes-simplex-virus-hsv/. Accessed 18/01/2022.","Ingram, B. The many presentations of Syphilis. J Dermatol Nurses Assoc [Internet]. 2016 Oct [cited 15 Jan 2022];8(5):318-324. Available from: https://journals.lww.com/jdnaonline/fulltext/2016/09000/the_many_presentations_of_syphilis.5.aspx DOI: 10.1097/JDN.0000000000000252","Jaishankar D, Shukla, D. Genital herpes: insights into sexually transmitted infectious disease. Microb Cell [Internet]. 2016 Sept [cited 15 Jan 2022];3(9):437-449. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5354570/ DOI: 10.15698/mic2016.09.528","Donovanosis. Australian STI Management Guidelines. https://sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/donovanosis/. Accessed 21/09/2023","Adil A, Goyal A, Quint JM. Behcet Disease. [Updated 2023 Feb 22]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470257/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89615"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11489"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89615","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89615"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-25T17:40:41+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-25T17:40:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4120"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107163"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":